Hint

Given an array of integers nums and an integer target, return indices of the two numbers such that they add up to target.

You may assume that each input would have exactly one solution, and you may not use the same element twice.

You can return the answer in any order.

 

Example 1:

Input: nums = [2,7,11,15], target = 9
Output: [0,1]
Explanation: Because nums[0] + nums[1] == 9, we return [0, 1].

Example 2:

Input: nums = [3,2,4], target = 6
Output: [1,2]

Example 3:

Input: nums = [3,3], target = 6
Output: [0,1]

 

Constraints:

    2 <= nums.length <= 104
    -109 <= nums[i] <= 109
    -109 <= target <= 109
    Only one valid answer exists.

 
Follow-up: Can you come up with an algorithm that is less than O(n2) time complexity?

Notes: 
Why "&"?
In short: & means "Reference."

It tells the computer: "Do not make a copy of this list. Just give me a link to the original one."
The Problem: "Pass by Value" (No &)

By default, when you pass a variable into a function, C++ makes a photocopy of it. This is called "Pass by Value."

Imagine your nums vector has 1,000,000 numbers in it.

    Without &: The computer has to pause, find a new empty space in memory, and copy all 1,000,000 numbers into that new space before the function can start.

    The Result: This is slow and wastes a huge amount of memory (RAM).

The Solution: "Pass by Reference" (With &)

When you add the &, you are using "Pass by Reference."

    With &: The computer just passes the memory address (like a shortcut or a URL) of the original vector.

    The Result: It is instant. No matter how big the list is, passing it takes zero time.

A Real World Analogy

Think of the vector as a huge textbook.

    Without & (Copy): You want to show me a page. You go to the photocopier, copy the entire 500-page book, and give me the copy. This takes forever!

    With & (Reference): You just hand me the actual book. I look at it immediately.

Why doesn't int target have an &?

You might wonder why we didn't write int& target.

    Vectors are big: They can hold millions of items. Copying them is expensive.

    Integers are tiny: An int is extremely small (usually just 4 bytes). Copying an integer is just as fast (sometimes even faster) than creating a reference link.

Summary

    Use & for big things: (Vectors, Strings, large Classes) to save speed and memory.

    Don't use & for small things: (int, bool, char, double) because copying them is cheap.

Pro Tip:
Since & gives the function access to the original list, the function could technically change the numbers inside it (like erasing data). If you want to use & for speed but want to make sure the function cannot change your data, you write const vector<int>& nums. This means "Look but don't touch!"


Time Complexity is how many steps the computer has to take as the input list gets better.

The Cheat Sheet: How to Find Complexity

You can usually figure it out just by looking at the loops in your code.
O(1) - Constant Time (The Best)

This means "Instant." The number of steps is always the same, no matter how huge the list is.

    How to spot it: No loops. Just basic math or checking a specific spot.

C++

// O(1) Example
int getFirst(vector<int>& nums) {
    return nums[0]; // Always takes 1 step, even if list has 10 billion items.
}

O(n) - Linear Time (Okay)

This means "One step per item." If you have 10 items, it takes 10 steps. If you have 1,000 items, it takes 1,000 steps.

    How to spot it: A single loop that goes from start to finish.

C++

// O(n) Example
void printAll(vector<int>& nums) {
    for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) { // Runs N times
        cout << nums[i] << endl;
    }
}

O(n2) - Quadratic Time (Slow)

This means "Square the input." If you have 10 items, it takes 100 steps (10×10). If you have 1,000 items, it takes 1,000,000 steps!

    How to spot it: A loop inside another loop (Nested Loops).

C++

// O(n^2) Example - YOUR CODE
for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {         // Outer loop (Runs N times)
    for (int j = i + 1; j < nums.size(); j++) { // Inner loop (Runs ~N times)
        // ... work ...
    }
}
// Total Work = N * N = N^2

