The Analogy: "The Detective's Notebook"

Imagine you are a detective trying to find a pair of suspects. You know their combined height must be exactly Target.

The Old Way (O(n2)):
You line up all the suspects. You pick the first one, measure them, and then compare them against every single other person in the line. Then you grab the second person and do it again. It takes forever.

The New Way (O(n) - The Hash Map):
You walk down the line of suspects just once. You carry a Notebook (this is the Hash Map).

    You stop at a suspect. Let's say he is 4 feet tall.

    The Target is 10.

    You do simple math: "I need someone who is 6 feet tall to make a match" (10−4=6).

    You check your Notebook: "Have I seen a 6-foot person before?"

        NO: Write down "Saw a 4-foot person at index 0" in the notebook. Move on.

        YES: You look in the notebook, see where the 6-foot person was, and BAM! You have your pair immediately.

The Tool: std::unordered_map

In C++, this "Notebook" is called an unordered_map. It stores two things:

    Key: The number we saw (e.g., "4").

    Value: Where we saw it (the index, e.g., "0").

This lookup is Instant (O(1)). You don't have to search the whole notebook.

